          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e50027c3-61f1-4d6a-b5a3-fb1fd8e32ee6.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 16:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-ambassador-meets-with-detained-wall-street-journal-reporter-257240ff</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-ambassador-meets-with-detained-wall-street-journal-reporter-257240ff<author><![CDATA[Ann M. Simmons]]></author><category>埃万格什科维奇</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>间谍</category><category>埃文·格什科维奇</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>埃文·格什科维奇</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>间谍</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine Inches Forward in Southeastern Counteroffensive]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>基辅军队挺进一个村庄并成功袭击第聂伯河<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835166/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="扎波罗热地区的乌克兰军人。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>扎波罗热地区的乌克兰军人。斯特林格/路透社<span>斯特林格/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133225"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133225"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/matthew-luxmoore" itemprop="url" rel="author">马修·卢克斯摩尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日中午 12:05 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-inches-forward-in-southeastern-counteroffensive-31747174"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰军队在东南部取得了进展，并成功突袭了南部的第聂伯河，俘获了一名俄罗斯高级军官，这推动了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其缓慢的反攻</a>。</p><p>据俄罗斯派驻官员称，乌克兰军队最近几天至少占领了乌罗扎因村的一部分。基辅尚未承认这一进展，但周日表示，俄罗斯军队收复乌罗扎因地区失地的尝试失败了。</p><p>乌克兰还声称特种部队在赫尔松南部地区第聂伯河上空的突袭取得了成功，周末在那里俘获了一名俄罗斯营指挥官。近几周来，乌克兰加大了对河流的袭击力度，分析人士称此举是为了拉伸<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-seeks-to-divert-ukrainian-forces-away-from-counteroffensive-80580e89" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯军队</a>。</p><p>自6月份利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方提供的武器</a>和在西方训练的旅发动大规模反攻以来，乌克兰一直在缓慢取得进展，但尚未取得重大突破。</p><p>最初使用新供应的西方坦克和装甲车突破<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mines-everywhere-ukraines-offensive-is-proving-a-hard-slog-270a1e4a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">俄罗斯坚固防线的</a>尝试在六月陷入停滞，此后的进展缓慢且成本高昂，因为乌克兰越来越依赖于使用小部队攻击来取得渐进战果的策略。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AC3C107B-9782-4818-8597-CDA6782368C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraine-inches-forward-in-southeastern-counteroffensive-31747174&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 2012 年停产后，“星光”导弹正在重新投入生产，以帮助乌克兰的防空。 《华尔街日报》研究了英国导弹如何在同类导弹中脱颖而出，以及为什么其独特的功能使其能够超越俄罗斯的反制措施。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>乌克兰进军乌罗扎因可能会加强其对邻近村庄斯塔罗马约尔斯克的控制，俄罗斯军事博客称该村庄为俄罗斯军队的重要前哨基地，直到上个月末被乌克兰占领。</p><p>周末在俄罗斯 Telegram 频道上分享的一段视频，随后军事分析人士对乌罗扎因郊区进行了地理定位，视频显示，当<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">集束弹药</a>在村庄附近爆炸时，俄罗斯士兵沿着道路逃离。</p><p>被占领的顿涅茨克的俄罗斯国民警卫队副司令亚历山大·霍达科夫斯基表示，乌克兰占领乌罗扎因的部分原因是俄罗斯未能用预备部队加强那里的防线，导致该村庄由在该地区战斗了数月的部队保卫。 。</p><p>他说，乌克兰正在向南几英里处的俄罗斯主要防线发起进攻，该防线由战壕、雷区和坦克障碍物组成。他说，俄罗斯在试图在村庄中站稳脚跟时正在遭受损失。</p><p>霍达科夫斯基在 Telegram 上发表的一篇文章中谈到在乌罗扎因周围作战的俄罗斯军队时说：“战斗是由我们现有的部队进行的。” “直接说吧：兵力并不充足。”</p><p>俄罗斯在被占领的扎波罗热地区派驻的官员弗拉基米尔·罗戈夫表示，俄罗斯在乌罗扎因周边地区的局势“困难且令人担忧”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835147?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名乌克兰士兵向巴赫穆特附近的俄罗斯阵地开火。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：LIBKOS/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他在 Telegram 上发帖称：“在这个村庄经过两周最激烈、最血腥的战斗后，敌人已成功进入乌罗扎因北部地区并巩固自己的阵地。”</p><p>汉娜·马利亚尔,</p>乌克兰国防部副部长周一表示，乌克兰正在东部和南部的几个轴线上取得进展，并补充说，经过本周的激烈战斗，乌罗扎因地区取得了“一定的成功”，但没有详细说明。<p></p><p>马利亚尔表示，在东部，乌克兰已经取得了一些小幅进展，继续向俄罗斯今年春天占领的巴赫穆特市的侧翼推进。她说，俄罗斯正在库皮扬斯克附近集结部队和装备，莫斯科军队希望从乌克兰手中夺回该地，并正在升级对莱曼镇的攻势，以回应基辅对巴克穆特的攻击。</p><p>马利亚尔表示，乌克兰近几个月在东部收复了超过15平方英里的领土，但在南部战线面临着俄罗斯的严重抵抗。</p><p>乌克兰还继续在赫尔松南部地区的第聂伯河上开展特种部队行动，俄罗斯军队占领该河以南地区，乌克兰控制北部，包括11月夺回的地区首府赫尔松。</p><p>乌克兰媒体周日分享了一段视频，视频显示据称在南部作战的俄罗斯营指挥官尤里·托莫夫少校被俘。</p>在乌克兰绑架者在场的情况下，在地图上标记俄罗斯阵地的位置。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835145?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰敖德萨遭受导弹袭击后，俄罗斯一直轰炸该港口城市。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰媒体周日还发布了一段视频，显示托莫夫谈到了他所在营的严重损失以及南部俄罗斯军队士气低落的情况。 《华尔街日报》无法核实该视频。</p><p>乌克兰官员表示，在被囚禁期间，托莫夫预计将向他的乌克兰上司透露有关俄罗斯军事行动的重要信息。</p><p> “现在他必须记住一切并展示出来，”南部敖德萨军事管理局发言人谢尔希·布拉楚克(Serhiy Brachuk)说。 “但我们可以向执行这次行动的战士们脱帽致敬，他们俘虏了数十名敌方士兵，夺取了弹药和武器，最重要的是抓获了这位可怜的营长。”</p><p>与此同时，俄罗斯周一对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰南部的敖德萨</a>发动了一波导弹和无人机袭击，加剧了对这座港口城市的持续轰炸，俄罗斯上个月退出了一项允许乌克兰从其港口出口谷物和其他食品的协议，紧张局势仍在继续。 。</p><p>乌克兰南部军事指挥部表示，俄罗斯在夜间对敖德萨的袭击中动用了 15 架无人机和 8 枚导弹。军方表示，所有无人机和导弹均被该市防空系统击落，但坠落炮弹的碎片损坏了几座建筑物并引发火灾。据称，三人受伤。</p><p>写信给马修·卢克斯摩尔： <a href="mailto:matthew.luxmoore@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">matthew.luxmoore@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 16:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-inches-forward-in-southeastern-counteroffective-31747174</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-inches-forward-in-southeastern-counteroffective-31747174<author><![CDATA[Matthew Luxmoore]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚历山大·霍达科夫斯基</category><category>弗拉基米尔·罗戈夫</category><category>汉娜·马利亚尔</category><category>谢尔希·布拉楚克</category><category>尤里·托莫夫</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentina’s Dollar Bonds Plummet After Far-Right Outsider Wins Primary Vote]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哈维尔·米雷 (Javier Milei) 在 10 月总统选举前的初选中获得大部分选票后，央行贬值比索的官方汇率<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835118?width=860&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">极右翼总统候选人哈维尔·米雷周日在布宜诺斯艾利斯的竞选总部发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alejandro pagni/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 11:24（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周一，阿根廷美元债券暴跌，政府贬值比索官方汇率，一天前，一位极右翼局外人士在十月大选前将自己定位为该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国的主要希望</a>。</p><p>周一早些时候，该国债券交易价格下跌约 10%。央行将比索的官方汇率贬值，比索贬值超过20%，至1美元兑换350左右。布宜诺斯艾利斯街头的比索黑市汇率略为疲软，约为 600 美元兑换 1 美元。</p><p>哈维尔·米莱 (Javier Milei) 是一位头发蓬乱的 52 岁经济学家，他对他所谓的“政治种姓”表示不满，他在周日的初选中获得的选票比中右翼“共同谋变”联盟和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">执政的庇隆主义运动的</a>得票数还多，引发了骚乱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">候选人</a>，经济部长塞尔吉奥·马萨。</p><p>投资者原本预计“共同谋变”联盟会在投票率较低的投票中表现更好。</p><p>芝加哥威廉·布莱尔投资管理公司的投资组合经理贾里德·卢表示：“低投票率和意外结果导致政治和市场不确定性增加。” “鉴于经济状况不佳，选民似乎要求变革。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">巴西和阿根廷领导人重新提出了共同货币的想法，以促进贸易并减少该地区对美元的依赖。 《华尔街日报》的萨曼莎·皮尔森解释了为什么它不太可能很快实施。照片：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>米莱是一位民粹主义新贵，他承诺关闭央行、用美元取代比索并削减支出，她获得了 30% 的选票。</p><p>在决定谁参加 10 月份第一轮总统选举的选举中，米莱击败了帕特里夏·布尔里奇 (Patricia Bullrich) 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">马萨</a>(Massa)。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与极不受欢迎的总统阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯相比，他对商业也更友好</a>。他获得了27.3%的选票。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 15:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>货币/货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>哈维尔·米雷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>钱</category><category>货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Musk vs. Zuckerberg Fight May Never Happen, but Italian Cities Are Still Jostling to Host It]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>科技巨头对决的可能性越来越渺茫，但这并没有阻止古代角斗士故乡的狂热兴奋<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835079/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社<span>阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-sylvers" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里克·西尔弗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a>似乎无法就是否以及何时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进行笼式比赛达成</a>一致。尽管如此，拥有著名考古场所的意大利城市仍在争相成为一场能够带来大规模全球宣传的活动的舞台。</p><p>上周，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">特斯拉</a>首席执行官<span class="company-name-type">马斯克</span>在他的社交媒体公司 X（前身为 Twitter）上发布的帖子在意大利各城市引发了热潮。 “相机画面中的一切都是古罗马的，所以根本没有现代的东西。我与意大利总理和文化部长进行了交谈。他们已经就一个史诗般的地点达成了一致。” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1689963696703848449" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">马斯克写道</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>母公司 Meta 的首席执行官扎克伯格<a href="https://www.threads.net/@zuck/post/Cv0Kc-yP2Wu" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">周日在竞争对手平台 Threads 上进行了反击</a>，指责马斯克没有认真参加拳击比赛，并对这场比赛表示怀疑。 “埃隆不会确认日期，然后说他需要手术，现在要求在我的后院进行一轮练习。如果埃隆认真对待一次真正的约会和官方活动，他知道如何联系我。”</p><p>这两位科技亿万富翁在六月份表示，他们将互相争斗。从那以后，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/sports/mark-zuckerberg-elon-musk-fight-cage-match-7b28d9c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">互相互相嘲讽</a>，但很少透露这场比赛的具体细节。</p><p>马斯克提到的古罗马让许多意大利人认为他指的是罗马城而不是帝国。罗马斗兽场显然是角斗比赛的有力竞争者。</p><p>但在意大利官员称公元 80 年竣工的罗马斗兽场过于脆弱之后，这场看似是世界上最知名的古迹之一的首轮淘汰赛很快就变成了一场混战。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmusk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 在人物模型的帮助下分析了为什么这场科技争吵实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>意大利文化部长根纳罗·桑朱利亚诺称赞马斯克和扎克伯格的战斗是一场“伟大的事件”，但没有透露可能的地点。该部和意大利总理办公室没有回应置评请求。</p><p>罗马斗兽场退出后，人们的目光转向了马克西穆斯竞技场，这座长椭圆形体育场距离酒店仅几步之遥。</p><p>在古代，马克西穆斯竞技场举办战车比赛，例如好莱坞史诗《宾虚》中描述的比赛。如今，这里偶尔举办摇滚音乐会，有时令当地人懊恼不已。本月早些时候，特拉维斯·斯科特的一场音乐会变得如此喧闹，以至于居民们表示他们以为发生了地震。</p><p>进入舞台右侧：《宾虚》中使用的电影布景，现在是罗马郊区电影主题公园 Cinecittà World 的一部分。该公园的首席执行官称该场地是两全其美，既提供了古老的氛围，又不玷污真正的纪念碑。</p><p>罗马政客们一直在推动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ostia-a-search-for-the-secrets-of-romes-port-1454089086?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在古罗马港口奥斯蒂亚安蒂卡（Ostia Antica）</a>建造一个相对较小的剧院，距离城市只有很短的火车车程。</p><p>意大利南部的卡拉布里亚地区也提出了自己的观点，地区主席提醒所有人，该地区是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-riace-bronzes-warriors-rescued-from-the-sea-1464385173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">里亚斯青铜雕像</a>的故乡，这是两尊古老的裸体战士雕像。别介意这两座巨大的雕像是 50 年前从海底打捞出来的，现在存放在博物馆里，它们起源于希腊，比罗马崛起早了几个世纪。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835080?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃隆·马斯克上周表示，这场比赛将在意大利举行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贡萨洛·富恩特斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“如果你正在寻找一个史诗般的地方，令人回味和迷人，陶尔米纳就是你的选择，”西西里镇镇长卡特诺·德卢卡 (Cateno De Luca) 在 X.陶尔米纳 (X. Taormina) 上写道，该景点在 HBO 节目中播出后迅速流行起来。 “白莲花”有一个古希腊剧院，可以看到西西里海岸线的全景。</p><p>一份竞争对手的提案来自那不勒斯附近的贝内文托市长，该市有一座罗马剧院，有时被称为罗马斗兽场的双胞胎，另一个提案来自巴西利卡塔南部地区的一个小镇，该镇也有一座罗马剧院。</p><p>庞贝市长提出了在这座被挖掘的古城中使用剧院的理由，这座古城在公元 79 年因维苏威火山爆发而被掩埋。</p><p>维罗纳竞技场是一座保存完好、比罗马斗兽场稍古老的圆形剧场，矗立在不幸恋人罗密欧与朱丽叶的故乡，上演大型歌剧作品。自称“爱之城”的维罗纳市长迄今为止一直保持沉默——也许是因为举办笼斗比赛看起来很尴尬。</p><p>一些意大利人认为，对于一个拥有如此丰富历史和古迹的国家来说，举办亿万富翁之间的打斗是不合适的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835082?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗马马克西穆斯竞技场一直在竞选主办这场比赛的机会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：格雷戈里奥·博吉亚/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835083?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西西里小镇陶尔米纳的古希腊剧院最近人气猛增。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼奥·帕里内洛/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>文化部好斗的副部长维托里奥·斯加尔比(Vittorio Sgarbi)经常介入意大利的文化战争，他表示自己根本不关心这场斗争，也不会观看。他表示，马斯克和扎克伯格可以使用任何潜在的场地，包括罗马斗兽场，只要他们付费。</p><p>斯加尔比说，文化部长桑朱利亚诺已就意大利是否应该主办这次活动征求他的意见。</p><p> “对我来说，这很好，”斯加尔比在接受《晚邮报》采访时回答道。 “他们会给你多少钱？一亿？”</p><p>桑朱利亚诺表示，马斯克和扎克伯格的任何资金都将用于科学研究和升级两家儿科医院。</p><p>斯加尔比表示，他会在这场斗争中支持马斯克，因为特斯拉首席执行官曾在议会演讲中称赞了他。</p><p>另一位反对派议员卡洛·卡伦达 (Carlo Calenda) 在 X 上写道：“我只是觉得令人震惊的是，意大利的文化遗产被提供给了两位想像白痴青少年一样战斗的亿万富翁。”“这不是他们付多少钱的问题。有些东西根本不卖。其中之一就是一个伟大国家的尊严和历史。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835084?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">维罗纳的竞技场是一座保存完好的圆形剧场，比罗马斗兽场稍古老。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mickael Chavet/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给埃里克·西尔弗斯（Eric Sylvers）： <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867<author><![CDATA[Eric Sylvers]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canada Tests the Limits of Its Liberal Immigration Strategy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新移民数量迅速增加，给住房、医疗和交通带来压力<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834831/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="加拿大去年迎来了超过一百万永久和临时移民。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>加拿大去年迎来了超过一百万永久和临时移民。大卫·瑞德/路透社<span>大卫·瑞德/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093529"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093529"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:00（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>渥太华——大量移民使加拿大成为近年来增长第二快的发达国家经济体，仅次于美国，因为它竞相<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">吸引来自世界各地的高技能工人</a>。</p><p>现在，新来者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开始限制</a>该国吸收他们的能力，使该国增长的一个重要引擎面临风险。</p><p>加拿大统计局称，这个拥有 4000 万人口的国家去年迎来了超过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-stretch-of-canadian-border-bustles-with-migrants-1503efb0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">100 万永久和临时移民</a>。人口涌入导致人口增长 2.7%；增加的105万人几乎相当于美国去年的增幅，而美国的人口是加拿大的八倍多。</p><p>加拿大官员表示，未来两年，他们将把永久新移民的数量增加近三分之一，其中大多数是技术移民，如木匠、计算机科学家和医疗保健工作者，他们符合基于绩效的积分制度。</p><p>该体系由总理贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau) 政府大力提倡，但于 20 世纪 60 年代首次开发，有助于推动经济增长、吸引企业家并填补技术职位空缺。它得到了加拿大政界的广泛支持，其目标是吸引世界上最优秀和最聪明的人才来到加拿大。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825356?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大的房价仍然位居世界最高之列。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡罗莱纳安德拉德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但新移民的数量增长如此之快，以至于分析师和新移民表示，这给<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">过热的房地产市场</a>火上浇油，给紧张的医疗系统带来压力，并堵塞了不习惯交通拥堵的城市的道路。</p><p>这也促使移民在选择加拿大时三思而后行。 27 岁的卡兰维尔·辛格 (Karanvir Singh) 来自新德里，是一名训练有素的会计师，在都柏林呆了四年后，于去年 11 月获得工作许可证来到多伦多地区。他说，考虑到房价、食品成本和公共交通的低迷，他正在重新考虑。</p><p>辛格说，加拿大“试图尽可能多地让所有移民来这里经营他们的经济，但他们错过了这样一个事实：他们必须建造一个地方，或开发一个地方……这样移民才能在这里生活。”</p><p>达拉斯联邦储备银行编制的数据显示，即使在利率快速大幅上涨之后，该国的房价仍然位居世界最高之列。分析师表示，由于住宅建设跟不上人口增长，加拿大房价比 2020 年水平高出 36%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825693?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">卡兰维尔·辛格 (Karanvir Singh) 是一名训练有素的会计师，去年 11 月抵达多伦多地区，他表示，他正在重新考虑是否留下来。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡兰维尔·辛格</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>约翰·帕萨利斯说：“当我们的政府决定将人口增长速度提高两倍而不考虑每个人的居住地点时，就会发生这种情况。”</p>多伦多房地产经纪公司 Realosophy Realty 总裁。<p></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TD" class="company-name">道明银行</a>经济学家在上个月的一份报告中预测，根据当前的人口趋势，满足预期需求所需的住房单位缺口可能会在短短两年内翻一番，达到 50 万套。</p><p> Aurika Tabassum 于 2014 年持学生签证从孟加拉国来到这里，学习人力资源管理。她现在在多伦多结婚，在一家招聘公司工作，并于六月得知加拿大授予她永久居留权。但她和她的丈夫买不起房，他们在多伦多北部租的公寓——两间卧室，这样亲戚从国外来访时可以留下来——花费了他们一半以上的税前工资，她说。</p><p> Tabassum 说，在美国的某些地区，“你可以花 30 万或 40 万美元购买一栋大房子。在这里，你连地下室都买不了。”塔巴苏姆说，她现在警告热衷于在这里定居的孟加拉国朋友和亲戚有关住房成本的问题。</p><p>加拿大以欢迎移民而闻名，并没有经历美国和荷兰等国家最近出现的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/immigration-backlashes-spread-around-the-world-142124bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">强烈抵制</a>。但渥太华 Abacus Data 上个月发布的新民意调查反映出了质疑，61% 的公民表示，政府的计划过于雄心勃勃，因为这对住房和医疗保健产生了负面影响。加拿大医学协会表示，该国的人口与医生比例在 36 个发达经济体中排名第 29 位，而经济合作与发展组织的数据显示，加拿大的医院床位容量是人均最低的国家之一跻身于富裕世界经济体之列。</p><p> “任何时候增加人口，尤其是在医疗资源紧张的环境下，都会产生影响，”加拿大医学协会主席阿利卡·拉方丹博士说。</p><p>以特鲁多为首的加拿大政府官员捍卫了该国的政策。直到上个月末仍担任加拿大移民部长的肖恩·弗雷泽 (Sean Fraser) 表示，来自海外的新工人的增加帮助该国从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-looks-to-immigration-to-boost-economic-recovery-11617105739?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疫情的经济深渊</a>中恢复过来。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834830?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以总理贾斯汀·特鲁多为首的加拿大政府官员为该国的移民政策辩护。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Adrian Wyld/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>弗雷泽在 6 月份回答问题的电子邮件中表示，新移民发挥了关键作用，“通过新想法、创新和庞大的数量来补充加拿大人才库，以帮助解决严重的劳动力短缺问题”。他说，加拿大正在让熟练的商人和护士更容易在该国定居，并补充说这将有助于缓解住房建设和医疗保健方面的紧缩。</p><p>加拿大央行行长蒂夫·麦克勒姆(Tiff Macklem)上个月在新闻发布会上表示，移民帮助劳动力市场降温，这是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-inflation-cools-in-may-as-gasoline-prices-drop-aa65ec96?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀降至</a>央行2%目标的先决条件。该国失业率连续三个月攀升，在 2023 年大部分时间保持在 5.0% 的历史低点后，7 月份达到 5.5%。</p><p> “另一方面，”麦克勒姆说，“这些新移民，他们也是新消费者，他们是新租房者，他们是新购房者，所以他们也增加了需求。”加拿大央行在过去16个月内<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-canada-lifts-interest-rates-warns-path-to-stable-inflation-at-risk-18462fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加息</a>10次，累计加息4.75个百分点，以抑制消费者支出、减缓通胀。</p><p>从历史上看，新移民涌向多伦多、温哥华和蒙特利尔等大城市，但现在他们也在较小的城市和郊区定居。</p><p> The total population of Canada&#39;s capital region, around Ottawa, grew by 8.5% between 2016 to 2021, according to the national census, and house prices there surged 84% in the same period, based on data from the Canadian Real Estate Association. In the Kitchener-Waterloo-Cambridge region, a technology and manufacturing hub 70 miles west of Toronto, the population grew 10% to 575,000. In the 2016-21 period, house prices more than doubled. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825439?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Immigrants are settling in smaller towns outside big cities, such as Bradford West Gwillimbury, about 33 miles north of Toronto.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: cole burston/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> As immigration has surged, Canada&#39;s gross domestic product per capita—widely used by economists to measure a country&#39;s standard of living—has declined. National Bank Financial said last month that Canada&#39;s per-capita output is on track to fall 1.7% in the second quarter from a year ago, and the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development predicts Canada&#39;s GDP-per-capita growth could be one of the lowest among developed-world economies over the next four decades.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should the US copy Canada&#39;s strategy around immigration?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Canada&#39;s aggressive immigration “camouflaged the real underlying problem in this country, which is a lack of business investment and productivity,” said David Rosenberg, former chief North American economist at Merrill Lynch and now head of Rosenberg Research. This is showing up in everything from stressed public-transportation, roads, healthcare and housing, he said.</p><p> Dale Renout is the pastor at Rawdon Street Baptist Church in Brantford, Ontario, where the population has risen 6.2% from a half-decade ago. Renout said he supports immigration but believes it is time that Canada limit the number of newcomers, based on his experience trying to help them, largely unsuccessfully, find affordable rentals. He also pointed to the emergence of traffic jams in Brantford.</p><p> “There&#39;s been no increase in hospital beds, no increase in road capacity,” Renout said. “I just don&#39;t know where new immigrants are going to go.”</p><p> Write to Paul Vieira at <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Table Outside? More Diners Say No Way]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Restaurants say heat waves, smoke have hurt their outdoor dining business <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001126271"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833543?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Customers are steering clear of patios during heat waves, hurting restaurant summertime sales.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Richard B. Levine/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001126271"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/heather-haddon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Heather Haddon</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wendy-guzman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Wendy Guzman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Stretches of severely high temperatures across the US are taking a toll on restaurants.</p><p> Customers are avoiding patios during heat waves, cutting into a key source of summertime sales for many restaurants, owners said. Visits in July and August declined from earlier in the year, industry data showed, with chains including Chuy&#39;s and Cheesecake Factory reporting a decline in outdoor business this summer.</p><p> “No one&#39;s sitting out in the patio at 100 degrees,” Steve Hislop, chief executive of Texas-based Chuy&#39;s, said during an Aug. 3 earnings call.</p><p> Utility expenses are also rising as restaurants run air conditioning at full blast for long stretches of time, operators and industry groups said.</p><p> Temperatures climbing to the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/june-hottest-on-record-heat-b222c05c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">highest levels in recorded history</a> this summer have hurt hospitality, sports, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-farmers-livestock-crops-ce555ffd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">agriculture</a> and many other businesses. In states such as Texas, weeks of days topping 100 degrees are expected <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to reduce overall economic productivity</a> .</p><p> Restaurants are contending with heat and smoke as many operators are fighting for sales from cash-strapped consumers, and dealing with high inflation in food, labor and other costs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833553?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cheesecake Factory reported a drop in outdoor business this summer.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maggie Shannon for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Diners overall at restaurants in Arizona, Florida and Georgia dropped between 6% and 8% in the first part of August compared with last year&#39;s period, according to OpenTable. The reservation tech company also recorded diner declines in other states running hot this summer, including Texas and North Carolina.</p><p> “This summer does feel different,” said Kelsey Erickson Streufert, chief public affairs officer for the Texas Restaurant Association trade group. “It&#39;s a little tougher to get people to come out.”</p><p> Employees working at restaurants and bars dipped 1.5% in July compared with the month prior, with steep declines in cities such as San Antonio, New Orleans and Phoenix that recorded high temperatures during the month, according to Homebase, a small business workforce app. The declines likely stemmed from extreme temperatures disrupting consumer spending and foot traffic, Homebase said.</p><p> Worker advocates are increasingly <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-is-it-too-hot-to-keep-working-in-most-states-companies-decide-9797ae18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">making heat an issue</a> in campaigns for improved conditions for restaurant workers. Some are pushing for better enforcement of existing standards and additional federal indoor heat regulations to provide employees breaks and water when temperatures rise.</p><p> “We&#39;ve seen 86 degrees on the coolest side of the kitchen,” said Ariana Lingerfeldt, a cook at an Asheville, NC, restaurant who is a member of the Restaurant Opportunities Centers United worker advocacy group, during an Aug. 9 event pushing for more heat standards. “The air conditioner is unable to keep up with the equipment.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="465" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833607?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Many restaurants set up patios in the early days of the Covid-19 pandemic, and now rely on them to drive summer sales.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Timothy Fox Photography</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some restaurant operators said they are giving their workers more water and rest breaks, since kitchen temperatures can climb steeply despite air-conditioning.</p><p> Many restaurants <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restaurants-spend-big-for-upgraded-outdoor-dining-with-quicker-service-elaborate-decor-for-winter-11633599000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">set up patios</a> in the early days of the Covid-19 pandemic, and have come to rely on them to drive summer sales. New York City, for example, is poised to make <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outdoor-dining-saved-restaurants-but-making-it-permanent-is-complicated-11648925954?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">expanded outdoor dining in roadways</a> permanent from April to November, and supporters say patios have helped restaurants maintain sales and jobs.</p><p> Now, some restaurant owners said those patio sales are drying up when temperatures surge, or wildfire smoke blows.</p><p> “When the sun&#39;s on it, it&#39;s literally scalding out there,” said Marc Hochmuth, general manager of City Social restaurant in downtown Chicago, which has a patio. Hochmuth said his business dropped about 20% overall when temperatures soared this summer.</p><p> Zoe Dean-Neil, a 20-year-old Pennsylvania resident who was on vacation in Chicago in August, said she opted to eat inside in the air conditioning after a day walking around in the heat. “I don&#39;t want to sit outside and sweat,” she said.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-east-coast-gets-a-taste-of-what-its-like-living-with-wildfires-f4330a14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Smoke drifting into the US</a> from Canadian wildfires also affected business at restaurants in parts of the country earlier this summer. John DuBuque, a 31-year-old management consultant from Chicago, said he tried to have a glass of wine outside during one heavily smoky period in the city, and regretted it.</p><p> “It was not the vibe,” said DuBuque, who said he now makes more outdoor dining decisions based on the air quality index. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=73DA72E0-DF39-4F23-973C-AEEBEF455473&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A massive heat dome across the American Southwest is driving temperatures in Phoenix and Las Vegas to record triple-digit highs. New Maxar satellite photos show how the growth of these cities is contributing to the crushing heat. Illustration: Luca Depardon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Restaurant owners are trying to work around the weather. Sue Rigler, owner of Hundred Mile Brewing Company in Tempe, Ariz., said she is misting and putting extra fans on her outside beer chilling units to keep them cool. She has also cut back on labor in response to slower sales that she attributes to the heat.</p><p> “July was a really hard month,” Rigler said. “We finally got a break at 108, and they call that a break.”</p><p> Tom Hutchinson, owner of La Posta de Mesilla and Hacienda de Mesilla in New Mexico, said his hotel and restaurants are promoting cold beers and margaritas to attract customers. He is also hoping to keep people coming to the outdoor space surrounding their adobe building at night when temperatures may fall to the 90s.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Have you been dining more indoors or outdoors this summer?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “We don&#39;t have humidity in our state and you can tolerate that,” he said.</p><p> Longer term, restaurant operators are trying to adjust to more climate-driven variables.</p><p> Avram Hornik, owner of the FCM Hospitality group of restaurants, bars and outdoor pop-up venues in Philadelphia, said his sales are down 30% this summer because of weeks of heat and rain. Smoky conditions in June didn&#39;t help, he said.</p><p> “I look at it such as being a farmer. The weather controls all,” he said.</p><p> Write to Heather Haddon at <a href="mailto:heather.haddon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">heather.haddon@wsj.com</a> and Wendy Guzman at <a href="mailto:wendy.guzman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wendy.guzman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa<author><![CDATA[Heather HaddonWendy Guzman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>Lodgings/Restaurants/Bars</category><category> Restaurants/Caterers</category><category> Full-service Restaurants</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>lodgings</category><category> restaurants</category><category> bars</category><category> caterers</category><category> full-service restaurants</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong Un Calls for Sharp Rise in North Korean Weapons Production]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The US and South Korea are set next week to begin major military drills, which Pyongyang calls rehearsals for war <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132369"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835000?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> North Korean leader Kim Jong Un checking out an armored vehicle, as he tours military factories.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: KCNA VIA KNS/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132369"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 7:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SEOUL—North Korean leader <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> called for a drastic increase in weapons production as the US and South Korea strengthen their military cooperation to counter the North.</p><p> For the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">second time in as many weeks</a> Kim visited military factories, this time observing the making of tactical missiles, mobile launch platforms and artillery shells on Friday and Saturday, Pyongyang state media reported on Monday. He ordered increased production of artillery shells for front-line units to be “fully prepared for coping with any war at any moment,” according to state media.</p><p> North Korea has become increasingly vocal about its weapons production and military strength in recent weeks. Last week, Kim convened military officials to discuss “major military actions” against South Korea, and at the meeting called for “full preparations for war,” according to state media, which didn&#39;t elaborate.</p><p> The US and South Korea are set next week to begin major military drills, which North Korea routinely refers to as rehearsals for invasion. This year&#39;s version of the annual Ulchi Freedom Shield— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-south-korea-revive-live-military-drills-after-four-year-hiatus-11661074202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">revived last year as a live-action exercise</a> —will be the largest ever, with tens of thousands of troops as well as member states of the United Nations Command, according to Seoul&#39;s military.</p><p> “The exercises are absolutely necessary to respond to the growing military threat from North Korea,” Lee Sung-jun, a spokesman for South Korea&#39;s Joint Chiefs of Staff said during a Monday briefing. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=901F4C0B-AEB7-4EE0-90AB-3AAD0B945CAA&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> North Korean media showed Leader Kim Jong Un taking Russian Defense Minister Sergei Shoigu around a hall full of weapons, including missiles and drones. The event comes as delegations from Russia and China visit the country for the 70th anniversary of the end of the Korean War. Photo: AFP PHOTO/KCNA VIA KNS<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>North Korea this year held massive military parades to mark <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korean-parade-puts-missile-production-prowess-on-display-11675937910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">75 years since the founding of its armed forces</a> and 70 years since the signing of the armistice ending fighting in the 1950-53 Korean War, a date North Korea calls <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-celebrates-major-holiday-with-special-guests-from-china-and-russia-fc3386fc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">“Victory Day.”</a></p><p> On Sept. 9, marking 75 years since the founding of the republic, will be a militia parade, likely meaning soldiers marching past more than weapons rolling by.</p><p> Anniversaries marking multiples of five or 10 years have been opportunities to boast the regime&#39;s economic as well military accomplishments. But the effects of sanctions and Pyongyang&#39;s self-imposed border closures have forced Kim to emphasize the military, said Park Won-gon, a professor of North Korean studies at Ewha Womans University.</p><p> “Kim&#39;s increasingly frequent appearances at military-related events and facilities show there aren&#39;t economic achievements for him to publicize, indicating the economy is struggling,” Park said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834999?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kim Jong Un visiting a munitions factory in an undated image released by North Korea on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: KCNA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> State media photos showed Kim, in a white jacket, driving a new utility combat armored vehicle and inspecting short-range missiles in production. North Korea has continued to expand its missile and nuclear program since <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-north-koreas-kim-end-nuclear-summit-early-11551334804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">talks with the US collapsed in 2019</a> . Pyongyang has fired more than 100 missiles since last year, including a test of a new <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fires-ballistic-missile-toward-japan-2c728f14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">solid-fuel intercontinental ballistic missile,</a> and showcased new attack drones at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">the Victory Day parade</a> last month.</p><p> The Kim regime has justified its military buildup as defensive, as Washington <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">deploys more strategic assets</a> to the Korean Peninsula and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korea-u-s-military-drills-could-use-nuclear-assets-president-yoon-suk-yeol-says-11672669292?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">expands military exercises</a> with South Korea.</p><p> The Ulchi Freedom Shield is a computer-simulated command-post exercise, which was downsized for four years under former South Korean President Moon Jae-in, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korean-president-to-visit-pyongyang-in-bid-to-revive-diplomacy-1537136720?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">sought diplomacy with North Korea</a> . This year&#39;s exercise will include 30 large-scale field-training events, compared with 13 last year. Along with US Army, Air Force and Marine personnel, the US Space Force will also take part in the joint exercises this year, according to the US Forces Korea.</p><p> Earlier this month, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Kim visited five weapons factories</a> , inspecting the production of engines for cruise missiles and drones. When Russian defense minister Sergei Shoigu</p> visited Pyongyang last month to attend the massive Victory Day military parade, Kim gave him a tour of a defense exhibition displaying North Korea&#39;s missiles, launcher trucks and drones.<p></p><p> US officials said Russia was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-is-again-turning-to-north-korea-to-replenish-ammunition-supplies-d79a5318?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">looking to buy more ammunition</a> from North Korea to replenish its supplies as the war in Ukraine drags on. Moscow and Pyongyang have repeatedly vowed to strengthen cooperation during the war, but denied any weapons deals. The UN Security Council has barred North Korea from testing missiles or selling weapons.</p><p> This Friday, President Biden is scheduled to host South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol and Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida at Camp David, where the three leaders are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-first-camp-david-summit-looks-to-align-allies-facing-china-threat-89626785?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">set to announce their countries will hold joint military exercises annually</a> . The US and its allies are knitting together radar, satellites and weapons systems to counter the North Korean nuclear and missile threat.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 11:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509<author><![CDATA[Dasl Yoon]]></author><category> Aerospace/Defense</category><category>工业品</category><category>Output/Production</category><category> New Products/Services</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Products/Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Kim Jong Un</category><category> output</category><category> production</category><category> new products</category><category> services</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>products</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>risk news</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ozempic Settles the Obesity Debate: It’s Biology Over Willpower]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Weight-loss drugs affect the brain in ways that help researchers understand how the body regulates weight <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834611/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/betsy-mckay" itemprop="url" rel="author">Betsy McKay</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ozempic and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-drugs-that-are-gaining-on-ozempic-71cdeb51?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">similar drugs</a> are transforming the world&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">understanding of obesity</a> . It isn&#39;t so much about willpower <strong>:</strong> It&#39;s about biology.</p><p> The success of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">powerful new class</a> of diabetes and weight-loss drugs shows how important chemistry is to determining a person&#39;s weight. The brain is the body&#39;s chief chemist, regulating appetite and making it difficult for many people to shed pounds and keep them off. The brain determines how much fat it wants people to carry, according to years of research <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mounjaro-eli-lilly-weight-loss-new-study-5f7661cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bolstered by the new drugs</a> .</p><p> The amount is like a setting on a dial, or what many researchers call a “set point” or “defended fat mass.” The brain maintains the dial setting or set point by regulating how much a person eats. Ozempic, its sister drug Wegovy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-mounjaro-weight-loss-drug-wegovy-eli-lilly-66f2906?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">and another, Mounjaro</a> , lower the dial setting, or set point, in effect by acting on the brain to reduce hunger and make a person feel full sooner, some obesity researchers say <strong>.</strong></p><p> The new set point lasts as long as a patient <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-stop-weight-loss-ea925ae1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is on the drug</a> , they say. Patients who ate a lot before they started taking one of the drugs <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-weight-loss-drugs-strains-relationships-327ab217?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">feel less hungry</a> and fill up more quickly—sometimes after one slice of pizza when they once ate the whole pie.</p><p> “This is not about willpower or personal choice,” said Dr. Florencia Halperin, an endocrinologist and chief medical officer of Form, a virtual medical weight-loss clinic. “This is about your brain driving behaviors.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fweight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Diabetes drugs could become an effective way to treat behavioral issues and addiction. WSJ&#39;s Daniela Hernandez breaks down the science of how they work and how they could change psychiatry forever. Photo illustration: Elizabeth Smelov<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The drugs and their insights into biology have arrived at a precarious point in the losing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pediatricians-recommend-weight-loss-drugs-for-obese-children-11673213563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">battle against obesity</a> . Although Americans spend billions of dollars a year to shed pounds, growing numbers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/more-states-show-prevalence-of-obesity-cdc-finds-11631734589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are overweight</a> . Nearly 42% of US adults have obesity, according to the <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> latest <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">government statistics</a> , up from 31% in 1999. So do <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/childhood.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">one in five</a> <strong>&nbsp;</strong> children.</p><p> People with obesity are more likely to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-decades-of-progress-america-backslides-on-heart-disease-11561129106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">develop heart disease</a> , stroke and diabetes. Treating them is driving more than $170 billion in <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0247307#pone.0247307.ref002" target="_blank" class="icon none">yearly costs</a> . Wegovy has been shown to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegovy-weight-loss-drug-heart-attack-stroke-570f435e?mod=hp_lead_pos6&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reduce cardiovascular risk</a> , and Mounjaro is being studied for additional health benefits.</p><p> The new medicines have put some long-held assumptions about weight and health on the chopping block. “What these drugs have proven is that patients are right: It&#39;s not their fault,” said Dr. Louis Aronne, an obesity treatment specialist and professor of metabolic research at Weill Cornell Medical College.</p><p> He and many other specialists who study obesity or prescribe the new drugs have advised or conducted studies for the companies making them. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834335?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An injection pen for Ozempic, one of the new class of drugs upending long-held assumptions about body weight.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jon Weisman</p> was about 300 pounds, prediabetic and at risk of heart disease when he sought help losing weight in 2020. The 46-year-old, who works in mortgage banking and real estate in Boston, had tried restricting food but always then felt hungrier. “I&#39;m not wired for 2,000 calories a day,” he said. “I&#39;m probably wired for 4,000.”<p></p><p> He went back on an earlier-generation weight-loss drug, Saxenda, that he had tried before. He lost about 30 pounds, but then hit a plateau.</p><p> In September 2021 he conferred with Dr. Halperin, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-you-cant-find-wegovy-the-weight-loss-drug-11670108199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">prescribed Wegovy.</a> His hunger quickly abated. He no longer craved onion rings, mac and cheese and other heavy foods that he once chowed down in marathon dinners with friends, now preferring greens and proteins. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835101?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jon Weisman is taking Wegovy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Weisman</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> He reached his goal weight of 180 pounds a couple of months ago, and is staying on the drug, which he sometimes has to call around to a few pharmacies to find. “This is something I am going to have to have treated for the rest of my life,” he said. He is off the two blood pressure medications he was on, has switched to a low dose of a cholesterol-lowering drug and is no longer prediabetic. He eats a little more now, to maintain rather than lose weight.</p><p> The obesity epidemic is a product of forces, old and new, that have collided in people like Weisman: human biology shaped over millennia of struggle to find sustenance; lives that are largely lived sitting down; and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cake-could-be-the-secret-to-teaching-kids-about-healthy-eating-habits-c4947362?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">abundance of cheap, processed foods</a> .</p><p> Potato chips, soda and other cheap processed foods are a big culprit because they are high in calories, sugar, salt and fat, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-craving-review-why-you-cant-eat-just-one-11635977800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">they are hard to put down</a> , studies suggest. People who lived for a month in a research facility at the National Institutes of Health ate more and <a href="https://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(19)30248-7" target="_blank" class="icon none">gained weight</a> on a diet of processed meats and cheeses, tater tots and other processed foods compared with when they were on a diet of vegetables, whole grains, fish and other unprocessed foods, according to a 2019 study.</p><p> For some people, high-calorie foods are especially problematic.</p><p> At least 1,500 genes are linked with weight. Some people are genetically predisposed to gain weight, depending on the combinations of variants in those genes, said Ruth Loos, a professor focused on the genetics of obesity at the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVO" class="company-name">Novo Nordisk</a> Foundation Center for Metabolic Research at the University of Copenhagen and at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai. These genes often act in the brain.</p><p> Primitive parts of the brain that control breathing, heartbeat and other essential functions collaborate with hormones and the central nervous system to determine how much fat the body wants to have and keep it at the set point. The system has been shaped by thousands of years of humans foraging to survive.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How have Ozempic and other weight-loss drugs changed your understanding of obesity?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The brain sends hunger signals when a person needs fuel to reach or maintain their set point, and signals a sense of fullness when they reach or exceed it. That is why people who lose weight fighting off an illness are ravenous once they recover, or why people <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-ozempic-treat-binge-eating-for-some-the-answer-is-yes-dbdc009f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">feel sick when they overeat</a> . It&#39;s also why people— <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4989512/" target="_blank" class="icon none">like some participants</a> in “The Biggest Loser” TV series—tend to regain weight even after they try to lose it, according to research.</p><p> The set point isn&#39;t set: It changes naturally throughout a person&#39;s lifetime. Babies lose body fat. Women gain weight during pregnancy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-if-we-could-get-rid-of-menopause-7adbc4e0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">and menopause</a> . It can make small changes, with a person gaining or losing a few pounds.</p><p> In a person with obesity, however, the set-point system has gotten out of whack <strong>,</strong> said Dr. Lee Kaplan, director of the Obesity and Metabolism Institute in Boston. The body-fat dial moves to a new higher set point.</p><p> Obesity causes overeating, rather than the other way around, Kaplan said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834339?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Scientists increasingly see the obesity epidemic as arising from the confluence of abundant high-calorie processed foods, sedentary lifestyles and human biology.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Chona Kasinger/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The new drugs are based on a hormone <strong>&nbsp;</strong> called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">glucagon-like peptide 1</a> , or GLP-1, secreted primarily in the lining of the gut in response to food, and in the brain. Drug hunters were initially interested in GLP-1 because it plays an important role in regulating blood sugar. The first GLP-1 drugs were approved to treat diabetes in 2005.</p><p> Wegovy is the only GLP-1 drug approved by the Food and Drug Administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/employers-cut-off-access-to-weight-loss-drugs-for-workers-cb277a44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">as an anti-obesity treatment</a> , while Ozempic, with a lower dose of the same active ingredient, semaglutide, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-runs-low-for-diabetes-patients-as-weight-loss-use-surges-286bf21a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is approved for diabetes</a> . The FDA is expected soon to approve Mounjaro for weight loss. Mounjaro, already cleared to treat Type 2 diabetes, mimics the action of a hormone called GIP in addition to GLP-1.</p><p> The medications essentially lower the set point by activating GLP-1 receptors in the hypothalamus and brain stem that regulate weight and appetite, said Randy Seeley, a professor of surgery and director of the Michigan Nutrition Obesity Research Center at the University of Michigan. The drugs also indirectly reach neurons in parts of the brain involved in reward sensations and impulse control.</p><p> “We are in a constant search to identify the most critical neurons that respond to these drugs,” he said.</p><p> Once a patient reaches a new set point, some of their appetite returns—they are no longer feeling overfed—but the medications keep them at their new level, Seeley said. If a patient stops taking the medication, the new set point no longer holds, which is why people regain weight, he said.</p><p> The set point concept is hard to prove definitively, some researchers say. The makers of the drugs, Novo Nordisk and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LLY" class="">Eli Lilly</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> say their drugs reduce hunger and increase satiety while a person takes them.</p><p> Researchers want to figure out what makes the set point go way up for some people, leading to obesity, Kaplan said: “For the moment, it&#39;s a black box.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11004b12-051f-4044-aa8a-823e293913dd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Betsy McKay at <a href="mailto:betsy.mckay@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">betsy.mckay@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173<author><![CDATA[Betsy McKay]]></author><category> wsjhealth</category><category>药品</category><category>Scientific Research Services</category><category> Healthcare/Life Sciences</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Specialized Drugs/Medications</category><category> Hormone Products</category><category> Diabetes Drugs</category><category> Medical Research Services</category><category> Drug Discovery/Development</category><category> Healthcare Support Services</category><category> Diagnostic/Medical Research Services</category><category> Biology</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Chemistry</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>肥胖</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> biology</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>chemistry</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>obesity</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>社会问题</category><category>pharmaceuticals</category><category> scientific research services</category><category> healthcare</category><category> life sciences</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>specialized drugs</category><category> medications</category><category> hormone products</category><category> diabetes drugs</category><category> medical research services</category><category> drug discovery</category><category> development</category><category> healthcare support services</category><category> diagnostic </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentines Back Far-Right Outsider in Presidential Primary]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哈维尔·米莱 (Javier Milei) 承诺解散央行，削减这个饱受通货膨胀、贫困和经济衰退打击的国家的支出<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132138"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834985?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Far-right congressman, Javier Milei, capitalized on anger against the political class to win the most votes in Argentina&#39;s primary election.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: alejandro pagni/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132138"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 12:25 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>阿根廷极右翼人士哈维尔·米雷(Javier Milei)承诺，如果当选总统，他将关闭各部委并削减开支。周日，他在十月选举前的初选中击败了保守派和执政的庇隆主义联盟，震惊了政治体制。</p><p>超过 80% 的选票已清点完毕，表示将推动阿根廷经济美元化并解散央行的国会议员米雷利用对政治阶层的愤怒，获得了 31% 的选票。这个拥有 4600 万人口的国家正在经历一代人以来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最严重的经济危机</a>，通货膨胀率高达 116%。每 10 个阿根廷人中就有 4 个生活在贫困之中，靠着日益贬值的货币艰难生存。</p><p> “如果我们今天不改变，唯一的命运将是变成世界上最大的贫民窟，”米雷在 8 月 7 日的竞选集会上对他的支持者说。“我不想要你们投票，所以你们给我权力，但还给你自由，这样你就可以成为自己命运的建筑师，我们可以结束这种让我们贫穷、通货膨胀和犯罪的状态，让国家走上增长之路。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>米莱是一位 5​​2 岁的长发经济学家，她在采访中抱怨统治阶级，并在演讲中冲上舞台，承诺要清洗在任机构和政客。他称自己为无政府资本主义者，愿意削减开支、减税并结束臃肿的国家。</p><p> “如果央行发放货币，就会造成损害，如果他们采取行动控制货币，就会造成损害，”他去年在接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示。 “不造成损害的唯一方法就是什么都不做，那我为什么要它们呢？我会关闭它，因为如果它运行的话就会存在风险。”</p><p>米莱比近年来执政但未能解决阿根廷严峻的经济问题的传统左翼和右翼政治联盟获得更多选票，令民意调查人员感到震惊。</p><p> “人们普遍对他的表现感到难以置信，”密切关注阿根廷的经济学人智库分析师尼古拉斯·萨尔迪亚斯说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834988?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Patricia Bullrich, the center-right coalition candidate, in Buenos Aires on Sunday night.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AGUSTIN MARCARIAN/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中右翼反对派联盟“共同变革”获得了约 28% 的支持。周日，选民们选择犯罪严厉的保守派人士、前安全部长帕特里夏·布尔里奇(Patricia Bullrich)作为十月选举中联盟的候选人，这是阿根廷人选举下一任领导人的两轮选举中的第一轮。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">执政的庇隆主义者</a>在过去 75 年的大部分时间里统治着阿根廷，获得了 26.69% 的支持率。该运动的候选人将是经济部长塞尔吉奥·马萨，他被认为比总统阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯和副总统克里斯蒂娜·基什内尔更加中间派和对商业友好。</p><p></p><p>米莱吸引了布宜诺斯艾利斯等城市周边贫困地区的年轻选民，他们对缺乏就业机会以及食品和衣服价格不断上涨感到愤怒。阿根廷在2018年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-imf-reach-deal-to-restructure-bailout-11643379805?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">接受国际货币基金组织440亿美元的救助</a>以避免货币危机后，一直无法抑制通货膨胀并阻止比索货币的快速贬值。</p><p> “我投票支持米莱，因为像大多数阿根廷人一样，我厌倦了同样的事情，所以我选择了彻底的改变，”失业的办公室清洁工阿尔达娜·戈麦斯(Aldana Gómez)说，她自称是“另一位失业的大多数人”。</p><p> “我只是期待改变，”22 岁的戈麦斯说，她和父母住在首都郊外的一个工人阶级地区。她说，过去的政府“都有机会，这就是为什么这个国家现在是一场灾难。”</p><p>当被问及为什么投票给新贵米莱时，商人塞萨尔·巴尔加斯 (César Vargas) 说：“很简单。我厌倦了被欺骗。”他说，近年来阿根廷人的生活变得更加糟糕。 “我希望阿根廷在短期内能够像智利或乌拉圭模式一样更加公正，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">巴西和阿根廷领导人重新提出了共同货币的想法，以促进贸易并减少该地区对美元的依赖。 《华尔街日报》的萨曼莎·皮尔森解释了为什么它不太可能很快实施。照片：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>周日的选举结果给阿根廷的政治体系带来了不确定性。尽管该国经济发生动荡，但近年来阿根廷的政治体系相对稳定，而其邻国则受到社会动荡和政治局外人崛起的打击。</p><p>阿根廷问题专家、威尔逊中心拉丁美洲项目主任本杰明·格丹表示：“阿根廷因其经济混乱而闻名，但在某种程度上，它因拥有相当可预测的政治体系而赢得了声誉，但现在情况已不再如此。” 。</p><p>米雷能够利用阿根廷的愤怒，尽管民意调查显示，许多选民并不一定同意他的政策建议，其中包括取消公共教育、建立出售器官的市场、扩大枪支拥有量和取缔堕胎。</p><p>格丹说：“现实是，他正在宣泄阿根廷目前几乎普遍的愤怒情绪。” “这与他的政策无关。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834896?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿根廷的工人们正在准备投票站。初选结果给该国政治制度带来了不确定性。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Erica Canepa/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>米莱面临着成为总统的艰苦斗争。民意调查机构称，他十月份的主要竞争对手似乎是布尔里奇。分析人士称，她可能会在大选中吸引许多保守派和中间派选民，他们担心米莱会在颠覆国家政治和经济体系方面走得太远。</p><p>米雷还可能面临投资者的抵制，他们担心他的治理能力和通过遏制公共支出和降低通胀所需的改革的能力。米莱可能很难在反对派控制的国会中通过立法。</p><p>在布宜诺斯艾利斯和其他城市的街道上，他将面临来自强大工会和迅速抗议的社会运动的强烈反对。</p><p> “如果改革不谨慎进行，可能会引发巨大的社会动荡，”格丹说。 “投资者对 Milei 有很多不安。现实是市场不喜欢不确定性。”</p><p>如果 10 月份没有候选人彻底获胜，排名前两名的候选人将在 11 月份进行决选。正如分析师预期的那样，没有左派、庇隆主义候选人出现的第二轮投票在阿根廷是闻所未闻的。</p><p>布宜诺斯艾利斯的民意调查专家塞尔吉奥·贝伦斯坦表示：“米莱和布尔里奇之间的决选将是前所未有的。” “这是一次反对通货膨胀的投票，一切照旧。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Silvina Frydlewsky 和 ​​Juan Forero 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>贫困</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Elections</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>帕特里夏·布尔里奇</category><category>哈维尔·米雷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>贫困</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Losers in the New World Order]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>巨额补贴和不断抬头的保护主义正在颠覆数十年的自由贸易。从英国到新加坡，较小的国家正在落后。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834926/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。 Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images <span>Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ed-ballard" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾德·巴拉德</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·埃蒙特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>世界上最大的经济体在一场残酷的竞争中提供巨额补贴，以赢得未来的产业。失败者：所有付不起钱的国家。</p><p>针对制造电池、太阳能设备和其他绿色技术的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新税收抵免</a>正在吸引<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量资金</a>涌入美国，欧盟正试图以自己的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-to-unveil-clean-tech-plans-in-bid-to-rival-u-s-china-a391ef5a" target="_blank" class="icon none">绿色能源</a>支持计划来应对。日本宣布计划借债 1500 亿美元，为绿色技术投资浪潮提供资金。所有这些国家都在努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-eu-advance-buyers-club-for-ev-battery-minerals-5288287e" target="_blank" class="icon none">减少对中国的依赖</a>，中国在电池和制造电池的矿物等领域处于领先地位。</p><p>现在，一些规模较小的企业正在被抛在后面。许多经济体都是灵活的经济体，在几十年的自由贸易中不断崛起，但在激进的产业政策新时代却处于不利地位。英国和新加坡等工业化国家在提供补贴方面缺乏与最大经济集团竞争的规模。印度尼西亚等新兴市场原本希望利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其自然资源</a>来攀登经济阶梯，但也受到了这种转变的威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>德国政府向英特尔提供了 110 亿美元的补贴，用于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-tsmc-to-build-first-european-chip-plant-in-germany-155e4d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">建设两座半导体工厂</a>，总理奥拉夫·肖尔茨 (Olaf Scholz) 称这是德国历史上最大的外国直接投资。政府承诺的融资远高于新加坡贸工部的年度预算。</p><p> “让我坦白地告诉你们：我们承担不起比大公司出价更高的代价，”副总理黄循财在最近的一次政治集会上对支持者说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834210?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英特尔首席执行官帕特·基辛格(Pat Gelsinger)和德国总理奥拉夫·舒尔茨(Olaf Scholz)于6月签署了一项协议，让英特尔在德国建造两家半导体工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chris Emil JanssEn/ddp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于许多在英国培育的科技公司来说，增长在于其他地方。英国电池技术初创公司 Nexeon 在政府资助的帮助下在牛津附近开发了自己的技术，去年筹集了超过 2 亿美元。它的第一家商业工厂将设在韩国，随后可能会在北美设立一家工厂。</p><p> “但遗憾的是，英国不是这样，”纳科星公司首席执行官斯科特·布朗(Scott Brown)表示。如果政府不加大对电池行业的支持，纳科星公司并不认为这种情况会发生改变。</p><p>英国为数不多的本土电池制造商之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/AMTE" class="">AMTE Power</a>表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>鉴于美国和欧洲提供的补贴存在差异，该公司可能会重新考虑在苏格兰设立一家耗资 2 亿多美元的工厂的计划。电动汽车初创公司 Arrival 去年表示，以税收优惠为由，希望将生产重点放在美国而不是英国。</p><p>作为《通货膨胀削减法案》的一部分，美国为清洁能源提供了 3690 亿美元的激励措施和资金， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-green-subsidies-are-attracting-billions-of-dollars-to-red-states-11674488426?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">外国投资也带来了意外之财</a>。德国汽车制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/BMW" class="company-name">宝马</a>刚刚在南卡罗来纳州破土动工建设一座新电池工厂。韩国公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hyundai-motor-lg-energy-to-build-4-3-bln-battery-jv-in-u-s-97991f73?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">现代和</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/066570" class="company-name">LG</a>宣布斥资 43 亿美元在佐治亚州建设电池厂。日本松下公司正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/panasonic-energy-kansas-to-partner-on-4-billion-ev-battery-factory-11657754596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">堪萨斯州建设一家工厂</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834214?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">工人们正在为堪萨斯州德索托附近的松下电动汽车电池工厂进行场地准备。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：查理·里德尔/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>解除全球化</h3><p>补贴竞赛标志着几十年来打破国家间贸易和投资壁垒的经济一体化又迈出了一步。</p><p>全球化将韩国和台湾等曾经贫穷的国家转变为高科技发达经济体，使数亿人摆脱了贫困。西方消费者获得了大量负担得起的消费品和更高的生活水平。技术进步和新的管理理念以及商品和金融资源也更加自由地在国家之间流动。</p><p>该模型的成本也很高。随着制造业工作转移到亚洲或前苏联国家，美国和西欧曾经繁荣的社区变得空心化。随着全球经济消耗更多的自然资源，环境问题日益凸显。随着外国资金涌入和流出，一些经济体面临着不稳定的资本外逃。</p><p>经济学家表示，放松全球一体化——无论是出于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/friend-shoring-might-be-bad-for-global-growth-inflation-11654437600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国家安全、地缘政治竞争还是供应链焦虑</a>的原因——都会带来自身的问题。尤其面临风险的是较小的发展中经济体，如果它们想要通过贸易实现更大的繁荣，就需要进入全球市场。</p><p> “整个世界正在变得更加内向，并远离开放的贸易和投资，”前美国财政部官员、资产管理公司 TCW Group 新兴市场董事总经理戴维·洛文格 (David Loevinger) 表示。 “欧洲、美国和中国正在进行补贴竞争，而这场竞争的失败者是财政资源较少的较贫穷经济体。”</p><p>对于那些希望利用绿色技术来推动本国经济发展的国家来说，西方对产业政策的拥抱可能尤其痛苦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834220?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工厂的一名工人。印度尼西亚希望利用其镍资源打造世界领先的电池产业。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>印度尼西亚雄心勃勃，希望利用其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">丰富的镍资源</a>打造世界领先的电池产业。但作为爱尔兰共和军的一部分制定的美国规定，拒绝向含有大量来自非美国自由贸易伙伴国家的矿物的电动汽车电池提供补贴。印度尼西亚就是其中之一。</p><p> “我们拥有所有的自然资源。我们有人力资源。我们是一个民主国家，”说</p>印度尼西亚工商会会长阿尔斯贾德·拉吉德（Arsjad Rasjid）接受采访。 “请不要关闭我们。”<p></p><h3>获奖者</h3><p>作为补贴竞赛的领先者，美国正在经历投资热潮。根据联合国的数据，美国去年吸收了全球约 22% 的外国直接投资，成为全球最大的接受国。这略低于 2021 年全球投资在疫情期间暂停后反弹时的 26%，但明显高于 2019 年的 13%。5 月份与制造业相关的建筑支出与 2019 年相比增长了 76%。人口普查局数据显示，去年同期经季节调整后的年增长率为 1,940 亿美元。</p><p>在英国，纳科星公司的资金凸显了美国财力扭曲竞争环境的力量。除了去年筹集的私人资本外，Nexeon 还从英国政府电动汽车行业基金处获得了 200 万英镑，价值约 255 万美元。</p><p>几周后，根据 2021 年基础设施法引入的电池行业资助计划，Sila Nanotechnologies 和 Group14 Technologies 这两家美国竞争对手都从能源部获得了 1 亿美元的资金。与 Nexeon 一样，这些公司正在生产用于电池阳极的硅基材料，以提高性能。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834213?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北卡罗来纳州达勒姆市的一家半导体制造商 Wolfspeed 的工人们正在观看美国总统乔·拜登 (JoeBiden) 的讲话，这是他三月份美国投资之旅的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅丽莎·苏·格里茨/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>澳大利亚央行前副行长、西澳大利亚矿业公司 Fortescue <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/FMG" class="">Metals</a>旗下绿色能源部门 Fortescue Future Industries 现任董事盖伊·德贝尔 (Guy Debelle) 表示，“美国项目的经济性简直令人难以想象<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ” Debelle 表示，该公司正在寻找投资机会，目前认为美国是最有可能的投资地点，因为美国的补贴可能会使项目的价格降低高达 60%。</p><p>欧盟正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-compete-with-u-s-clean-tech-tax-breaks-by-loosening-subsidy-rules-87a7d334?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">准备自己的一揽子支持计划</a>，放宽成员国给予工业的补贴限制。到 2030 年，欧盟希望绿色转型所需的 40% 关键技术在欧盟生产，包括太阳能设备（目前由中国主导的行业）、风力涡轮机和电池。</p><p>据 Benchmark Minerals Intelligence 估计，自 IRA 宣布以来，衡量在建项目产能的美国电池生产线已增长 67%，目前与欧洲的规模相当，欧洲同期增长了 26%。收集行业数据的英国公司。</p><h3>英国脱欧问题</h3><p>对于英国来说，全球贸易的转变发生在一个特别尴尬的时刻，英国在 2020 年离开欧盟后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-rishi-sunak-tries-free-market-recipe-to-fix-britains-woes-2aa177b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直在努力</a>制定全球经济的新路线，这意味着它不再能够轻松进入其庞大的单一市场。</p><p>英国脱欧支持者表示，英国可以与其他国家达成双边贸易协议，并加大全球化力度。此后，自由贸易的势头陷入停滞，现在似乎正在倒退。</p><p>哥伦比亚商学院气候经济学家格诺特·瓦格纳表示：“在英国脱欧公投期间，没有人知道我们会看到美国产业政策的复苏。”</p><p>现在，英国政府面临着来自国内经济各个角落的呼吁，要求通过重振产业战略来应对全球经济的干预主义转向。</p><p>英国汽车业近期因捷豹路虎母公司选择<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在英国新建电动电池工厂而</a>得到提振，但绿色补贴总体规模仍远远落后于美国</p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834215?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英国财政部长杰里米·亨特面临着引入重振工业战略以应对全球经济干预主义转向的压力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tayfun Salci/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>财政部长杰里米·亨特承诺在今年秋天公布英国的应对措施，但淡化了预期，并表示英国不会“在一些扭曲性的全球补贴竞赛中与我们的朋友和盟友针锋相对”。他表示，英国将寻求将资金投向英国具有明显竞争优势的领域。</p><h3>新联盟</h3><p>前世界银行贸易专家查德·鲍恩表示，对于无法竞争的国家来说，一个解决方案是拉近富裕贸易伙伴的距离，并从其产业政策中受益，就像加拿大和墨西哥通过与美国的自由贸易协定所做的那样华盛顿特区智库彼得森国际经济研究所的官员表示，印度尼西亚政府正在参与美国主导的印度-太平洋经济繁荣框架，该经济协定希望能够改善其矿产的市场准入。</p><p>去年，投资部长巴利勒·拉哈达利亚 (Bahlil Lahadalia) 表示，印度尼西亚将寻求组建一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mineral-rich-developing-nations-demand-bigger-piece-of-the-ev-pie-d1421603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">类似欧佩克 (OPEC) 的镍镍卡特尔组织</a>，以回应电动汽车制造国的保护主义。镍是一种电池矿物，印度尼西亚的产量占主导地位。欧佩克模式的组织将与其他主要出口国协调镍生产水平，以确保价格上涨。</p><p>分析师对该计划表示怀疑，部分原因是其他镍生产商不想疏远美国和中国等强大的贸易伙伴。拉丁美洲的左翼领导人也提出了类似欧佩克的锂生产商组织的想法，但尚未付诸实施。</p><p>印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍、铝土矿和锂等矿产实施了出口限制，并要求外国公司在该国建立加工设施，作为出口的条件。</p><p> “我不喜欢这些政策，但它们显然很受欢迎，”瑞士圣加仑大学国际贸易和经济发展教授西蒙·埃文内特(Simon Evenett)说。 “显然，这会推高价格，并增加不确定性和风险。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834218?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工综合体的景观。印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍和其他矿物实施了出口限制。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —伦敦的大卫·卢诺 (David Luhnow) 和悉尼的斯图尔特·康迪 (Stuart Condie) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给Ed Ballard（ <a href="mailto:ed.ballard@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ed.ballard@wsj.com）</a> 、Jason Douglas（ <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com）</a>和Jon Emont（ <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53<author><![CDATA[Ed BallardJason DouglasJon Emont]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>机械</category><category>电池</category><category>Industrial Electronics</category><category>工业品</category><category>可再生能源设备</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>可持续发展/可持续发展</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>容